Analyzing Conference Disparity in the NBA with R

Mein En Lee

02/23/22

Introduction

Using data from the 2005-06 to 2020-21 NBA seasons, I analyzed conference disparity in the NBA. How strong is the conference disparity? Is the disparity significant? Is it getting worse?

Throughout this project, there are guiding questions on how to apprach the datasets. Based on the analysis, I recommended Machine Learning models in order to make data-driven decisions within the NBA.

Note:

Throughout this document, the season column represents the year each season started. For example, the most recently completed season, 2020-2021, is in the data as season = 2020.

Datasets

Please check out my github repository: github.com/mein-lee/NBA_conference_disparity to view the datasets.

combined_team_vs_team_records.csv' has rows for each team in each season with columns representing matchup records against every team in the NBA in that season. For example, the 2016-17 Golden State Warriors won all four regular season matchups against the Los Angeles Clippers. Therefore the 'LAC' column of the 2016 Warriors row contains the value '4-0'. Let's get started!

library(tidyverse)
standings <- read_csv("combined_standings.csv")
team_v_team <- read_csv("combined_team_vs_team_records.csv")

Conference Standings

Question 1

QUESTION: What is the overall win % to one decimal place (e.g. 41.3%, 74.9%) of teams in the Western Conference against teams in the Eastern Conference through the 2005-2020 regular seasons? If the West has more wins than losses against the East, your answer should be a number greater than 50% and vice versa.

joined <- merge(standings, team_v_team, by = c("season", "bb_ref_team_name"))
joined[is.na(joined)] = "0-0"

# Remove West teams to form West-East dataframe
west_only <- joined[joined$conference == "West",]
west_teams <- unique(west_only$team_short)  
west_east <- west_only[, !(colnames(west_only) %in% west_teams)] 

# Use substring to sum wins and losses
wins <- 0
loss <- 0
nrows <- c(1:nrow(west_east))
for (row in nrows){
  wins <- wins + sum(as.numeric(substring(west_east[row,12:26],1,1)))
  loss <- loss + sum(as.numeric(substring(west_east[row,12:26],3,3)))
}

overall <- round((sum(wins) / sum(wins + loss))*100, 1)

ANSWER 1: 55.7%

Question 2

QUESTION: Out of the past 16 years (2005-2020), how many years has the Western Conference had more wins than losses against the East?

# Group by (season, conference) and calculate win_pct of each group
group_season_conference <- standings %>% 
                        group_by(season, conference) %>%
                        summarise(wins_sum = sum(wins), 
                                  losses_sum = sum(losses),
                                  group_win_pct = wins_sum / 
                                    (wins_sum + losses_sum))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'season'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
# Determine conference with higher win_pct of each season
higher_win_pct <- group_season_conference %>% 
              group_by(season) %>%
              slice(which.max(group_win_pct))

# Number of times each conference has more wins than losses (higher win_pct)
table(higher_win_pct$conference) %>% as.data.frame()
##   Var1 Freq
## 1 East    1
## 2 West   15

ANSWER 2: 15 out of 16 years.

Question 3

QUESTION: In which year was the disparity between the conferences most extreme? What was the inter conference win-loss record (in the format WEST WINS - EAST WINS) in that year?

# Calculate disparity within conferences throughout the seasons
disparity_df <- group_season_conference %>% 
          group_by(season) %>%
          summarise(conference, wins_sum, disparity = diff(wins_sum)) %>%
          arrange(desc(disparity))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'season'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Point Margins and Schedules

Question 7

In this next series of questions we are going to look at the strength of schedule by examining teams’ opponents’ point margins.

First, calculate the average point margin for each team’s opponents in each year, weighting by the number of times the teams played. For example, if team A played against team B once and team C twice, and team B had a season average point margin of +2 and team C had a season average point margin of -3, team A’s opponents would have an average point margin of (2 - 3 - 3) / 3 = -1.33. There is no need to display the results of this calculation here, you are going to use it for the next few questions.

# Rearrange columns
joined <- joined[,c(1:14,16,15,17:41)]

# Total games played with each opponent
for (col in c(12:41)){
  joined$opp <- (as.numeric(substring(joined[,col],1,1))
                + as.numeric(substring(joined[,col],3,3)))
  # Rename new columns
  colnames(joined)[ncol(joined)] <- paste("total_", 
                                          colnames(joined)[col], sep="") 
}
# Total games played with opponents 
joined$total_games <- apply(joined[,c(42:71)], 1, sum) 

# Point margin of each team throughout the seasons
joined$point_margin <- (joined$points_scored_per_game -
                        joined$points_allowed_per_game)

# Use nested for-loop for total opponent point margin
joined$total_opp_point_margin <- 0
for (season in seq(1,480,30)){
  for(opp in c(0:29)){
    for (team in c(0:29)) {
    joined$total_opp_point_margin[season+opp] <-
      (joined$total_opp_point_margin[season+opp] +
       joined$point_margin[season+team] *
         joined[season+opp, team+42])
    }
  }
}
# Opponent's average point margin
joined$oppAv_pm <- joined[,74] / joined[,72]

QUESTION: What was OKC’s opponents’ average point margin (to two decimal places) in the 2016 season?

okc_opp_av_pm <- round((joined[(joined$team_short == 'OKC') & (joined$season == 2016),75]),2)

ANSWER 7: 0.32

Question 10

PART (a): What do you conclude about the relative strength of schedule for the two labeled teams (DAL 2011 and LAL 2019) (compared to all the rest of the teams) at the top of the plot? Please answer in 1 sentence.

ANSWER 10 (a): Compared to other teams, the two labelled teams had a tough schedule due to their opponents’ high point margins.

PART (b): Do you have any hypotheses as to why teams from 2019 and 2011 appear at the extremes of this graph? Please answer in no more than 3 sentences.

ANSWER 10 (b): An NBA Lockout occurred in 2011, and the Covid-19 pandemic have impacted the 2019-2020 NBA season. Both events caused teams to play fewer games, and a small sample of games fails to standardize team point margins. This produces abnormal values that are plotted at the extremes of this graph.

Logistic Regression

Question 11

QUESTION: Fit a logistic regression model on all of the data 2005-2020 predicting the chance a team makes the playoffs from only its win % in that season. What are the coefficients?

joined$playoffs <- as.factor(joined$playoffs)
reg <- glm(playoffs ~ win_pct, data=joined, family = 'binomial')
aa <- reg$coefficients[1] #intercept
bb <- reg$coefficients[2] #win_pct

ANSWER 11: Intercept: -20.88, win_pct: 42.40

Question 12

QUESTION: Using your model from the previous question, what is the probability that a team with exactly a 50% win rate will make the playoffs (rounded to the nearest decimal, e.g. 44.7%)?

round(exp(aa+bb*.5)/(1+exp(aa+bb*.5))*100,1)
## (Intercept) 
##          58

Question 14

We are going to investigate whether it’s possible that the relationship you found in the previous question could be reasonably explained by randomness. We’re only looking at 30 teams over 16 years, so sample size might be a concern. To do this, you will perform a permutation test.

For each of 10,000 iterations, randomly reorder the conference labels so that in each iteration, there are 15 random teams labeled as East and 15 teams labeled as West. For example, in a given iteration, we might have assigned OKC to the East and BKN to the West, but MIA might still be assigned to East. For each iteration, fit a new logistic regression model with the same variables as in question 13 (predicting making the playoffs from win % and is_west) and extract the is_west coefficient. Save all 10,000 is_west coefficients in a vector or dataframe.

set.seed(425)
joined$sim_conf <- 0
sim_df <- joined[, c("win_pct", "playoffs")]
iswest_coef <- c()

for (iter in c(1:10000)) {
  # Get random row indices, assign to West
  assign_west <- sample(1:30,15)
  row <- rep(0,30)
  row[assign_west] <- 1
  sim_df$is_west <- rep(row,16)
  #Fit logistic regression
  reg_sim <- glm(playoffs ~ win_pct + is_west,
                 data=sim_df, family ='binomial')
  # Extract coefficient
  iswest_coef[iter] <- reg_sim$coefficients[3]
}

PART (a): Make a ggplot comparing these 10,000 randomized is_west coefficients to the is_west coefficient you observed in question 13.

ANSWER 14 (a):

iswest_coef <- as.data.frame(iswest_coef)
iswest_coef$Style <- 'Simulation'

plot_q14 <- iswest_coef %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=iswest_coef, fill=Style))+
  geom_histogram(bins = 100)+
  xlim(-3,2)+
  ylim(0,300)+
  geom_segment(aes(y=75, xend=-2.75, x=-2.5,yend=20),
               arrow = arrow(length=unit(.5, 'cm')))+
  annotate('text', x=-2.875,y=90, label='Observed Coefficient', size=3)+
  labs(x='Western Conference Log Odds Effect on Playoff Chances (Controlled for Win%)',
       y='Count',
       title='1000 Simulations of Playoff Chances from randomly assigned conference')+
  theme_hc()+

Short Answer (Modeling)

Question 15

Two rookies come into the league and each play the same number of minutes. Rookie A shot 37/100 from 3 and rookie B shot 20/50 from 3. The general manager asks you which player you expect to be a better three point shooter long term. You have a week to work on this hypothetical project.

PART (a): What kind of data and information would you collect in order to answer this? Describe the features you’d use and the model you’d build to answer the question. You don’t need to actually do the work here, just describe your process. Please limit your response to no more than 5 sentences.

ANSWER 15 (a): Features: 3PT%, FT%, and a delta parameter for each feature to track the change in a player’s shooting percentage from his first to last college season. Using college 3PT% on its own is not a good predictor because the three-point line distance is different than NBA’s, but FT% will demonstrate a prospect’s pure form. A Decision tree model of depth 5 would predict what quartile a player’s 3-point shooting percentage would be, which would indicate whether a player will be a serviceable 3-point shooter.

PART (b): If you had to choose today without doing any further research, would you pick player A or player B? Why? Please limit your response to no more than 2 sentences.

ANSWER 15 (b): Player A attempted more shots within the same time frame, shows agility and ability to perform under pressure, and provides a larger sample size.

Question 16

QUESTION: You are studying offensive rebounding as part of your job as Data Analyst with an NBA team. You are trying to create a model that will help predict when there will be an offensive rebound.

Your first model is a GBM (gradient boosted machine) that includes the location data (at the time the ball hits the rim) and height for all 10 players on the floor. It outputs a prediction for the percentage chance each player will collect the rebound.

Your second model is a logistic regression model that includes the shot distance, the number of players who crash the boards, and the distance to the rim for the closest two offensive and defensive players. This model outputs a prediction for the percentage chance the offensive team secures the rebound.

In no more than 4 sentences, how would you decide which model to move forward with? Why?

ANSWER 16: Logistic regression uses features that seem to be better predictors. This model also provides a more straightforward prediction than GBM.

Question 17

QUESTION: Your coach hears about the project and is interested in the tradeoffs between offensive rebounding and transition defense. He asks you to expand the research you have been doing into a study to help him determine when/how many players he should send to crash the offensive boards.

How would you use one of the models described above to answer the question for the coach? (Please select one of the two models to write about for this portion of the question.) What other research would be necessary to effectively answer this question for the coach? Describe, in general terms, your plan to answer the coach’s question and what you would plan to present to him. Please answer this question in no more than 6 sentences.

ANSWER 17: First, we should study the correlation between the number of “crashers” on each missed shot and the opponent’s subsequent transition offensive opportunity. The data to collect will be: 1) Type of shot taken, 2) Number of players crashed, 3) Did they rebound? If so did they score?, 4) If they did not rebound, did the opponent get a transition opportunity?, and 5) Did they score off that Transition Opportunity? If the study shows an inverse relationship between number of “crashers” and the opponent’s subsequent transition offensive opportunity, and if the logistic regression model from Q16 predicts a high percentage chance the offensive team secures the rebound, then the coach should place greater emphasis on crashing the board.
